  "prompt": "Why wasn't John Williams hired to write the soundtrack to Rogue One?",
  "response": "John Williams was not hired to compose the soundtrack for \"Rogue One: A Star Wars Story\" primarily because the film's director, Gareth Edwards, and the production team opted for a different musical approach for this standalone entry in the Star Wars saga. Instead of Williams, they brought in composer Michael Giacchino to create the score.\n\nGiacchino has a strong background in scoring films and has collaborated with Edwards before on projects like \"Monsters.\" The decision to choose a different composer allowed the filmmakers to explore a unique musical style that matched the tone and narrative of \"Rogue One,\" which is considerably darker and different from the main episodic films in the Star Wars franchise. \n\nAdditionally, producing a score that complements the distinct atmosphere of the standalone film was a priority, and Giacchino's work was well received, helping to create a memorable auditory experience that fit the film's vision.",
